getTypeOfInputs

public java.lang.Class[] getTypeOfInputs()
Description copied from interface: Operation
Class types of the inputs. If the inputs are unbounded, the last supplied class type will be assumed for all inputs with a higher index. E.g., if {Boolean,FSAModel} are supplied, the first input will be Boolean and all remaining inputs are assumed to be of type FSAModel. This type extension is applied only when the number of inputs is unbounded (i.e., when Operation.getNumberOfInputs() returns -1).

Whenever possible, please use the general interfaces from the package model.* (such as FSAModel) instead of specific implementations.

public java.lang.String[] getDescriptionOfInputs()
Description copied from interface: Operation
User-readable and understandable description for each input argument. If the inputs are unbounded, the last supplied description will be assumed for all inputs with a higher index. This type extension is applied only when the number of inputs is unbounded (i.e., when Operation.getNumberOfInputs() returns -1).

filter

public java.lang.Object[] filter(java.lang.Object[] inputs)
Description copied from interface: FilterOperation
Performs the operation directly on the input/output arguments. The inputs accepted by this method have to be of the same number, type and semantics as the inputs for Operation.perform(Object[]). The outputs produced by this method have to be of the same number, type and semantics as the outputs from Operation.perform(Object[]). Since some inputs may serve as outputs, they have to be included in the array with outputs.

Specified by:
filter in interface FilterOperation
Parameters:
inputs - inputs to the operation (must conform to the types described in Operation.getTypeOfInputs())
Returns:
outputs of the operation (must conform to the types described in Operation.getTypeOfOutputs()). The inputs which were modified have to appear in the array of outputs.
See Also:
Operation.perform(Object[])
